entry.content:
PlatformSensorReaderWinrtBase::StartSensor() has

```
  if (!reading_callback_token_) {
    // Convert from frequency to interval in milliseconds since that is
    // what the Windows.Devices.Sensors API uses.
    unsigned int interval =
        (1 / configuration.frequency()) * base::Time::kMillisecondsPerSecond;

    auto hr = sensor_->put_ReportInterval(interval);
```

the `reading_callback_token_` check makes any further StartSensor() calls that occur when the optimal frequency changes in PlatformSensor::UpdateSensorInternal() not to do anything. In other words, as far as I can see once a PlatformSensorWin and an accompanying reader are created with a frequency, this frequency will be used until it is stopped. This doesn't affect the Win32 backend.

# Steps to reproduce the problem
1. add DIV to the page
2. add css to make "fullscreen overlay": 
div {
		position: fixed;
		font-size: 52px;
		inset: 0;
		background: green
	} 
3. add css to make unexpectedly previously added DIV not full-screen
div {
  justify-self: center;
  align-self: center;
}

# Problem Description
With an update from current version i've got an issue that if you have DIV stretched with a "position: fixed; top: 0; left:0; right:0; bottom: 0;", it is unexpected that in that case now "justify-self: center" or "align-self: center" makes it not a full-screen already, it ruined markup at 200 my websites because this update changed previously implemented behaviour of the following css rules =/

I came with a Version 122.0.6261.69 (Official Build) (arm64)

# Summary
Fixed-position "fullscreen overlay" DIV not full-screen with "justify-self: center" is unexpected.

